\scap{2}{WORK THESE PROBLEMS}

\pcap{2}{a}{Problem A}
The rest mass of a $\pi^+$ (``pi-plus'') meson is about
140\,MeV/$c^2$.
If a $\pi^+$ is traveling at 0.8\,$c$, compute its energy in MeV and momentum
in MeV/$c$.

\pcap{2}{b}{Problem B}
In the decay of a $\Lambda^0$ (``lambda-zero'')
particle, at rest, to a neutron (n) and a $\pi^0$ (``pi-zero''), use
conservation of energy and momentum to show that the momentum of the neutron is
104\,MeV/$c$.
%
\begin{center}\begin{tabular}{l c l}
mass of $ \Lambda^0 $ & = & 1115.63\,MeV/$c^2$ \\
mass of $        n  $ & = & 939.5656\,MeV/$c^2$ \\
mass of $    \pi^0  $ & = & 134.9739\,MeV/$c^2$ \\
\end{tabular}\end{center}
%
\begin{itemize}
\item [Note:] (momentum)$^2 = k^2 v^2 m_0^2 = (k^2 - 1) m_0^2 c^2$ is a useful
identity that you can easily prove.

\item [Note:] For further decay problems see, ``Review of Particle
Properties,'' {\it Physics Letters}, Vol.\,239, April 12, 1990.
\end{itemize}

